ows a well-circumscribed heterogeneous mass in the pancreatic head with central hypoattenuation. <b>(e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image of the mass shows central signal hyperintensity, with a hypointense rim. (Case courtesy of Christine O. Menias, MD, Phoenix, Arizona.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190184&amp;id=fig7e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="SRCC in a 62-year-old woman with a pancreatic head mass. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an exophytic hypoattenuating pancreatic head mass (arrowhead), with upstream dilatation of the main pancreatic duct. (b, c) Diffusion-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show diffusion restriction with a low apparent diffusion coefficient. (d, e) Axial T2-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show homogeneous hyperintensity compared with the remaining pancreatic parenchyma (d) and homogeneous enhancement after administration of intravenous contrast media (e). (Case courtesy of Christine O. Menias, MD, Phoenix, Arizona.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190184/asset/images/large/rg.2020190184.fig8a.jpeg" height="1350" width="1577" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. SRCC in a 62-year-old woman with a pancreatic head mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an exophytic hypoattenuating pancreatic head mass (arrowhead), with upstream dilatation of the main pancreatic duct. <b>(b, c)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show diffusion restriction with a low apparent diffusion coefficient. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show homogeneous hyperintensity compared with the remaining pancreatic parenchyma <b>(d)</b> and homogeneous enhancement after administration of intravenous contrast media <b>(e)</b>. (Case courtesy of Christine O. Menias, MD, Phoenix, Arizona.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190184&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="SRCC in a 62-year-old woman with a pancreatic head mass. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an exophytic hypoattenuating pancreatic head mass (arrowhead), with upstream dilatation of the main pancreatic duct. (b, c) Diffusion-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show diffusion restriction with a low apparent diffusion coefficient. (d, e) Axial T2-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show homogeneous hyperintensity compared with the remaining pancreatic parenchyma (d) and homogeneous enhancement after administration of intravenous contrast media (e). (Case courtesy of Christine O. Menias, MD, Phoenix, Arizona.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190184/asset/images/large/rg.2020190184.fig8b.jpeg" height="1331" width="1570" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. SRCC in a 62-year-old woman with a pancreatic head mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an exophytic hypoattenuating pancreatic head mass (arrowhead), with upstream dilatation of the main pancreatic duct. <b>(b, c)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show diffusion restriction with a low apparent diffusion coefficient. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show homogeneous hyperintensity compared with the remaining pancreatic parenchyma <b>(d)</b> and homogeneous enhancement after administration of intravenous contrast media <b>(e)</b>. (Case courtesy of Christine O. Menias, MD, Phoenix, Arizona.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?d