 pancreatic duct. (b, c) Diffusion-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show diffusion restriction with a low apparent diffusion coefficient. (d, e) Axial T2-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show homogeneous hyperintensity compared with the remaining pancreatic parenchyma (d) and homogeneous enhancement after administration of intravenous contrast media (e). (Case courtesy of Christine O. Menias, MD, Phoenix, Arizona.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190184/asset/images/large/rg.2020190184.fig8e.jpeg" height="1330" width="1572" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. SRCC in a 62-year-old woman with a pancreatic head mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows an exophytic hypoattenuating pancreatic head mass (arrowhead), with upstream dilatation of the main pancreatic duct. <b>(b, c)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show diffusion restriction with a low apparent diffusion coefficient. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR images of the mass (arrowhead) show homogeneous hyperintensity compared with the remaining pancreatic parenchyma <b>(d)</b> and homogeneous enhancement after administration of intravenous contrast media <b>(e)</b>. (Case courtesy of Christine O. Menias, MD, Phoenix, Arizona.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190184&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="UC in a 35-year-old man with a history of recurrent heartburn and epigastric pain. (a) Photograph from gross pathologic examination shows an ill-defined pancreatic body and tail tumor with a whitish cut surface, measuring 6 cm. (b) Endoscopic US image with fine needle aspiration shows a hypoechoic mass in the pancreatic body and tail with cystic structures (arrowhead). (c, d) Photomicrographs from histopathologic evaluation show a variety of histologic appearances not defined by one direction of differentiation, including pleomorphic cells and osteoclast-like giant cells (arrowhead in c) and spindle cells (d). (e) Photomicrograph of the remaining pancreatic parenchyma specimen shows chronic pancreatitis and pancreatic intraepithelial neoplasia III lesions. (f–h) Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show an exophytic pancreatic body and tail mass (arrowhead) with direct invasion into the liver and subcapsular hemorrhage (* in g and h)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190184/asset/images/large/rg.2020190184.fig9a.jpeg" height="1084" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. UC in a 35-year-old man with a history of recurrent heartburn and epigastric pain. <b>(a)</b> Photograph from gross pathologic examination shows an ill-defined pancreatic body and tail tumor with a whitish cut surface, measuring 6 cm. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic US image with fine needle aspiration shows a hypoechoic mass in the pancreatic body and tail with cystic structures (arrowhead). <b>(c</b>, <b>d)</b> Photomicrographs from histopathologic evaluation show a variety of histologic appearances not defined by one direction of differentiation, including pleomorphic cells and osteoclast-like giant cells (arrowhead in c) and spindle cells <b>(d)</b>. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph of the remaining pancreatic parenchyma specimen shows chronic pancreatitis and pancreatic intraepithelial neoplasia III lesions. <b>(f–h)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT images show an exophytic pancreatic body and tail mass (arrowhead) with direct invasion into the liver and subcapsular hemorrhage (* in <b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190184&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div clas